Title: AI-Based Stock Trading Strategy using Machine Learning
1. Introduction

Stock market prediction is a challenging problem due to its highly dynamic and stochastic nature. Prices are influenced by multiple factors such as economic indicators, global events, and investor sentiment.

Machine Learning provides a data-driven approach to analyze historical patterns and make predictions about future price movements.

2. Objective

The main objectives of this project are:

To predict stock price direction (up or down)
To develop a machine learning-based trading strategy
To evaluate strategy performance using backtesting
To compare model performance with market returns

3. Methodology

The project follows these steps:

Data Collection

Historical stock data is collected using the Yahoo Finance API via the yfinance library.

Feature Engineering

Several technical indicators are created:

Returns (percentage change)
Moving averages (MA5, MA10)
Volatility (rolling standard deviation)
Momentum
RSI (Relative Strength Index)
Target Variable

The target variable is defined as:

1 → if next day price increases
0 → if next day price decreases

4. Machine Learning Models

Two models are used:

Logistic Regression
Simple linear model
Works well for binary classification
Random Forest
Ensemble learning method
Handles non-linear relationships
Reduces overfitting

5. Data Splitting

Time-based splitting is used:

Training data: Before 2023
Testing data: After 2023

This avoids data leakage and simulates real-world prediction.

6. Model Evaluation

Evaluation metrics include:

Accuracy
Confusion Matrix
Classification Report

7. Backtesting Strategy

Trading signals are generated based on prediction probabilities.

If probability > 0.6 → Buy signal
Else → No trade

Strategy returns are calculated and compared with market returns.

8. Results
Model accuracy is approximately 50%, which is expected due to market randomness.
The strategy shows improved risk management by reducing losses compared to the market baseline.
Random Forest performs slightly better than Logistic Regression.

9. Concepts Covered
Supervised Learning
Classification Algorithms
Feature Engineering
Overfitting and Underfitting
Bias-Variance Tradeoff
Time Series Data Handling

10. Conclusion

The project demonstrates that Machine Learning can be applied to financial markets. While prediction accuracy is limited due to the stochastic nature of stock prices, the model helps in reducing risk and making systematic decisions.

11. Future Scope
Add more technical indicators (MACD, Bollinger Bands)
Use Deep Learning models (LSTM)
Include multiple stocks
Deploy using Streamlit
